Rating: 0
I made this last night for a New Years Eve dinner party, and it was a smashing success. I had a really large tenderloin weighing over 7 pounds, so wasn't sure how long it would take to cook. I cut back a little on the pepper for the rub, but otherwise followed the recipe exactly. After bringing the beef to room temperature, it took approximately 45 minutes in the oven to reach 125 degrees which gave me medium on the ends and medium rare in the middle. The sauce cooked down in about 25 minutes in a saucepan over medium low heat. I made that the day before and brought it to room temperature prior to serving -- I didn't try and rewarm it, and it was great. Rave reviews on both the meat and the sauce. A definite keeper! One thing to note -- be sure your oven is clean prior to cooking at this high a temperature. I learned that the hard way a few years ago!

Rating: 4
Made this last night for Christmas dinner, and my family raved! It was the first time I prepared this recipe (a little risky for a special dinner), yet it seemed fool proof ... and it was! This recipe is the type you'll use again and again. The roast and sauce are amazing following the recipe. My family likes pepper so the quantity of pepper was not a concern, but they like (not love) horseradish and each of them said the horseradish flavor in the sauce was both mild and delicious. I roasted two garlic bulbs instead of one, and each of them loved the garlic flavor. I added 15 minutes to the end of the roasting period, and I achieved rare, medium rare results with the end tips/slices being almost well done (my family likes a variety). I served with small red potatoes and green beans just like the photo and it was an easy and delicious combination. My husband asked that I keep this recipe to make again in the future. What a success!

