Made for a dinner party for 6 adults, and it was exceptional. Made rub as directed. We were worried about overcooking so took out a bit earlier and it was a bit too rare - so I think recipe as written would be perfect. Some guests felt the pepper crust was a bit too much - I personally loved it. The horseradish cream (or "horseradish butter" as we called it) was delicious and a great accompaniment - it did take closer to an hour to reduce and I personally found it a bit too thick. But the taste was wonderful. Very "fancy" and easy to make. Served with carmelized shallot mashed potatoes, roasted carrots and roasted broccoli with asiago cheese...with White Chocolate Bread Pudding for dessert. great combination.

Rating: 4
This is an excellent recipe. I made this for a dinner party for 6 people. I got a tenderloin that was a little under 3 lbs and it was the perfect amount. A notes about cooking times: The cream took much longer to reduce than 20 minutes. Mine took probably took 40. I used 1/4 cup of pepper on the beef rub instead of 1/2 and it was plenty. My tenderloin took much longer to cook than what the recipe stated - it took about 45 minutes to get it to 130 degrees, which was a perfect medium rare. My oven is high end and brand new, so I don't think it was a calibration issue. Also, if you make the cream sauce earlier in the day at have it in the fridge, know that it will get quite firm. It's best at room temperature, so make sure to take it out of the fridge a good half hour or more before you serve it.

